KINDER MORGAN NORTH TEXAS PIPELINE LLC
STATEMENT OF OPERATING CONDITIONS FOR INTERRUPTIBLE TRANSPORTATION SERVICE RENDERED PURSUANT TO SECTION 7(C) BLANKET CERTIFICATE AND SUBPART G OF PART 284 OF THE REGULATIONS OF THE FEDERAL ENERGY REGULATORY COMMISSION (“COMMISSION”)
Article I. Introduction
1. Kinder Morgan North Texas Pipeline LLC (“KMNTP”), a Delaware limited partnership, owns and operates facilities wholly within the state of Texas for the purchase, sale and transportation of Natural Gas. KMNTP is a “Hinshaw” pipeline pursuant to Section 1(c) of the Natural Gas Act of 1938 (“NGA”), is exempt from the provisions of the NGA, and is subject to the original jurisdiction of the Railroad Commission of Texas pursuant to Tex. Rev. Civ. Stat. Ann. arts. 6050, et seq., and 1446(e) (Vernon Texas Statutes, 1994). KMNTP owns and operates approximately 82 miles of 30” natural gas pipeline between Lamar and Kaufman Counties, Texas, and also traversing Collin, Delta, Hunt and Rockwall Counties, Texas (collectively the “Facilities”). On June 20, 2005 in Docket No. CP05-87-000, the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (“Commission”) granted to KMNTP a blanket certificate of public convenience and necessity pursuant to Section 7(c) of the NGA and Subpart G of Part 284 of the Commission’s regulations (the “Blanket Certificate”) authorizing the transportation of natural gas in interstate commerce to the same extent and in the same manner that intrastate natural gas pipelines are authorized to engage in such activities, transactions and services pursuant to Section 311 of the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978 (“NGPA”) and Subparts C and D of Part 284 of the Commission’s Regulations. 2. As required by Subpart G of Part 284 of the Commission’s regulations, KMNTP is filing this Statement of Operating Conditions (“Statement”) in accordance with Section 284.123(e) of the Commission’s regulations for the purpose of setting forth the general terms and operating conditions under which KMNTP will provide interruptible gas transportation services in the Facilities for qualified Shippers pursuant to the authorizations granted by the Blanket Certificate. 3. The rules and regulations of the Commission govern all services provided pursuant to the Blanket Certificate. In the event that any term or provision in an executed Agreement for service pursuant to the Blanket Certificate is inconsistent with such rules or regulations or this Statement, the rules, regulations and this Statement will control and the Agreement will be deemed modified accordingly.
Article II. Transportation Services Subject to the provisions of this Statement, KMNTP will provide interruptible transportation service pursuant to the Blanket Certificate. Interruptible transportation service in the Facilities will be service for receipt and delivery of gas on an as-available, interruptible basis. KMNTP shall not be obligated to receive, transport or deliver any minimum quantity of gas. Either party, in its sole discretion, may interrupt, suspend or curtail the receipt or delivery of gas at any time and from time to time with no liability of any kind or character to the other party.
Article III. Eligibility of Shipper 1. In order to be eligible for service hereunder, Shipper must represent and warrant that it is either (i) an “interstate pipeline” within the meaning of Sections 2(15) and 311 of the NGPA, or (ii) a “local distribution company served by an interstate pipeline” within the meaning of Sections 2(17) and 311 of the NGPA, or (iii) otherwise authorized to arrange transportation on behalf of such interstate pipeline or local distribution company. Shipper shall indemnify and hold KMNTP harmless from all suits, actions, liabilities, damages, costs, losses, expenses (including attorney’s fees) and regulatory proceedings arising out of or in connection with breach of said warranty. 2. If, subsequent to commencement of transportation service pursuant to the Blanket Certificate, KMNTP has reason to question Shipper’s fulfillment of the warranty set forth in Paragraphs (a) above, KMNTP may refuse to accept Shipper’s tendered deliveries and may continue refusal until Shipper satisfies KMNTP of its complete fulfillment of such warranty. 3. Prior to commencement of service, KMNTP may require Shipper to supply KMNTP with credit information as set forth in Section X.– Creditworthiness of Shipper of Appendix A, attached hereto, in order that KMNTP may make reasonable inquiry into Shipper’s creditworthiness and obtain adequate assurance of Shipper’s solvency and ability to perform. If KMNTP, in its sole judgment and discretion, determines that Shipper’s creditworthiness is inadequate, KMNTP shall not be required to provide transportation service pursuant to the Blanket Certificate.
Article IV. Requests for Transportation Service KMNTP may decline to provide transportation service pursuant to the Blanket Certificate if Shipper has not made an appropriate request to KMNTP for such Blanket Certificate transportation service and has not executed an Agreement with KMNTP regarding same. In requesting Blanket Certificate transportation service, Shipper shall provide to KMNTP, in writing, the following:
a.) Shipper - the exact legal name and type of entity; mailing and street address; and the name, address and telephone number of a primary contact for Shipper regarding the transportation arrangement. b.) Gas Quantities - statement of the total and maximum daily quantities (in MMBtu’s) of gas, or an estimate thereof, to be received, transported or delivered by, or for the account of, Shipper. c.) Term of Service – the date service is requested to commence and terminate. d.) Receipt and Delivery Points - The Points of Delivery and Receipt for all gas tendered to KMNTP for transportation service pursuant to the Blanket Certificate shall be at the interconnection of KMNTP’s and Shipper’s (or any third-party’s, as may be applicable) facilities, or at such other points, as specified in Shipper’s Agreement with KMNTP.
Article V. Availability of Service 1. Non-Discriminatory Service - KMNTP will provide interruptible transportation services for qualified Shippers pursuant to the Blanket Certificate, without undue discrimination or preference within the meaning of Sections 284.8(b)(1) and 284.9(b)(1) of the Commission’s regulations, including undue discrimination or preference in the quality of service provided, the duration of service, the categories, prices or volumes of natural gas to be transported, or Shipper classification, or undue discrimination or preference of any other kind; subject to (i) this Statement, including the General Terms and Conditions attached hereto, or such reasonable terms and conditions as may be established from time to time by KMNTP without undue discrimination or preference, (ii) all applicable legal and regulatory requirements and (iii) the terms and provisions contained in Agreements negotiated and entered into between KMNTP and qualified Shippers. 2. Capacity available for Blanket Certificate transportation services shall be subject to: (i) KMNTP’s own requirements, (ii) the availability of excess capacity in the Facilities not required for its own use from time to time, (iii) the availability of capacity sufficient to provide the service, and (iv) the availability of sufficient capacity for KMNTP’s intrastate non-jurisdictional transportation Shippers.
Article VI. Priority of Service If cumulative Shipper requests for interruptible gas transportation service in the Facilities pursuant to the Blanket Certificate exceed the capacity of the Facilities to provide such service, then access to capacity at such Facilities shall be based on Shipper’s position in the priority queue, established as follows for both intrastate and Blanket Certificate customers: a) to all firm customers; b) to the extent that there is insufficient capacity to serve all firm customers, to each firm customer on a pro rata basis; c) to all interruptible customers paying the maximum interruptible rate, on a first-come, first served basis based upon date of receipt of a valid request as described in Article IV hereof; d) to the extent that two or more interruptible customers having the same first-come, first served priority are paying the maximum interruptible rate, on a pro rata basis; and e) to the extent that interruptible customers are not paying the maximum interruptible rate, on the basis of price; provided, however, that if two or more interruptible customers are paying the same price that is not the maximum rate, on a pro rata basis.
Article VII. Operating Conditions 1. In carrying out its day-to-day operations, KMNTP in its reasonable discretion shall determine the manner in which its Facilities will be utilized and in which services or requested services will be provided. 2. KMNTP shall not be required to provide Blanket Certificate transportation service if: a.) providing such service would cause KMNTP to have insufficient capacity or operational capability to meet its existing contractual obligations; or b.) providing such service would require KMNTP to purchase or increase purchases of gas; or c.) providing such service would, in KMNTP’s reasonable judgment, be detrimental to KMNTP’s system operations; or d.) all facilities necessary to effectuate the transportation are not in existence at the time the request for Blanket Certificate transportation is made. 3. The availability of KMNTP’s Facilities to Shipper is subject to all restrictions and restraints imposed upon KMNTP’s ownership of such Facilities. KMNTP shall be under no obligation to construct pipeline, compression or any other facilities for the receipt, transportation or redelivery of gas hereunder. 4. In order that KMNTP may maintain its status as a non-jurisdictional “Hinshaw” pipeline, and may be fully cognizant of any acts or events that could affect its status or operations, Shipper shall obtain advance approval from KMNTP before KMNTP’s Facilities are used to transport gas for any party other than as specified in Shipper’s original request for Blanket Certificate transportation service. 5. KMNTP’s maximum obligation to accept and redeliver gas shall be specified in the Agreement between Shipper and KMNTP. 6. KMNTP shall not be required to perform service on behalf of any Shipper that fails to comply with any and all of the terms of this Statement and the General Terms and Conditions attached hereto and with the terms of such Shipper’s Agreement with KMNTP.
Article VIII. Rates 1. KMNTP's maximum rates for interruptible transportation services rendered pursuant to the Blanket Certificate and for fuel and gas lost or unaccounted for were approved by the Commission in Docket No. CP05-87. 2. At KMNTP’s sole option, KMNTP may provide a discount from the maximum approved rates for KMNTP’s Blanket Certificate transportation by written notice to Shipper. Nothing herein shall obligate or require or be construed to obligate or require KMNTP to offer such a discount. 3. KMNTP reserves the right to file for higher maximum rates during the term of any Agreement and the maximum rates which Shipper agrees to pay shall, unless otherwise agreed, be revised to equal the approved maximum rates.
Article IX. Adoption of General Terms and Conditions
The General Terms and Conditions for Interruptible Gas Transportation Service Rendered pursuant to Section 7(c) Blanket Certificate and Subpart G of Part 284 of the Regulations of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (herein referred to as the “General Terms and Conditions”) constitutes a part of this Statement and are attached hereto as Appendix A and made a part hereof. Such General Terms and Conditions shall also be attached to and made a part of each Agreement entered into pursuant to this Statement between KMNTP and Shippers. APPENDIX A
KINDER MORGAN NORTH TEXAS PIPELINE LLC
GENERAL TERMS AND CONDITIONS FOR INTERRUPTIBLE GAS TRANSPORTATION SERVICE RENDERED PURSUANT TO SECTION 7(C) BLANKET CERTIFICATE AND SUBPART G OF PART 284 OF THE REGULATIONS OF THE FEDERAL ENERGY REGULATORY COMMISSION
SECTION I. DEFINITIONS
1. The term “Agreement” as used herein shall mean an Interruptible Gas Transportation Service Agreement between Transporter and Shipper pursuant to Transporter’s Blanket Certificate. 2. The term "billing month", as used herein, shall mean a period of time beginning at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the first day of a calendar month and ending at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the first day of the following calendar month. 3. The term "Blanket Certificate", as used herein, shall mean that certain blanket certificate of public convenience and necessity pursuant to Section 7(c) of the NGA and Subpart G of Part 284 of FERC’s regulations authorizing Transporter to transport natural gas in interstate commerce to the same extent and in the same manner that intrastate natural gas pipelines are authorized to engage in such activities, transactions and services pursuant to Section 311 of the NGPA and Subparts C and D of Part 284 of the Commission’s Regulations. 4. The term "Btu", as used herein, shall mean British Thermal Unit or Units and shall be defined as the quantity of heat required to raise the temperature of one (1) pound avoirdupois of pure water from fifty-eight and five-tenths degrees Fahrenheit (58.5° F.) to fifty-nine and five-tenths degrees Fahrenheit (59.5° F.) at a constant pressure of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch absolute (14.73 psia). 5. The term “Business Day”, as used herein, shall mean Monday through Friday, excluding Federal Banking Holidays. 6. The term "cubic foot of gas", as used herein, for the purpose of measurement of the gas delivered to Transporter or Shipper hereunder and for all other purposes, unless otherwise specifically provided, is the amount of gas necessary to fill a cubic foot of space when the gas is at an absolute pressure of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch absolute (14.73 psia) and at a base temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60° F.). 7. The term "Day", as used herein, shall mean a period of 24 consecutive hours beginning at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time. 8. The term "Equivalent Quantity", as used herein, shall mean that quantity of gas which is thermally equivalent to the quantity of gas delivered by Shipper to Transporter on any one Day (less fuel used and gas lost or unaccounted for in transport). 9. The term “federal”, as used herein, shall refer to the institutions of the United States of America and the term “governmental authority”, as used herein, shall refer to authorities of the United States of America, including but not limited to FERC, or to authorities of the State of Texas, including but not limited to the Railroad Commission of Texas. 10. The term “FERC”, as used herein, shall mean the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any successor governmental authority. 11. The terms “fuel and gas lost or unaccounted for” and “Fuel and GLU”, as used herein, shall mean the gas used by Transporter in compression, and/or metering, or otherwise lost in providing gas transportation service. 12. The terms "gas" and "natural gas", as used herein, shall mean natural gas as produced in its natural state whether or not stored or processed prior to receipt by Transporter or Shipper hereunder, natural gas that has been previously liquefied and restored to its gaseous state prior to such receipt and gas synthesized or manufactured from oil, naphtha, coal or any other material and that meets the quality standards contained in these General Terms and Conditions. 13. The term “Gas Daily Price”, as used herein, shall mean the price published in each day’s issue of Gas Daily under the heading “Daily Price Survey” for “East Texas-North Louisiana” for “NGPL, Texok zone” under the column “Midpoint. For gas delivered on a Saturday, Sunday or other day on which the above set forth prices are not published, the Gas Daily Price shall be that for the next following day on which such prices are published. Should Gas Daily and/or any of the subject indices therein cease to be published, Transporter may substitute for same an index or indices, or other methodology, reasonably calculated to achieve a similar economic result.
14. The term "heating value", as used herein, shall mean the number of Btu produced by the complete combustion, at constant pressure, of the amount of gas which would occupy a volume of one (1) cubic foot at a temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60° F.), if saturated with water vapor and at a constant pressure of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch absolute (14.73 psia) and under standard gravitational force (acceleration of 980.665 centimeters per second per second) with air of the same temperature and pressure as the gas when the products of combustion are cooled to the initial temperature of the gas and air and when the water formed by combustion is condensed to the liquid state. The gross heating value so determined shall be corrected from the conditions of testing to that of the actual condition of the gas as delivered to Transporter or Shipper hereunder (including the conversion from saturated to dry conditions) expressed in Btu per cubic foot and reported at a pressure base of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch absolute (14.73 psia); provided, however, if the gas as so delivered contains seven (7) pounds or less of water vapor per one million (1,000,000) cubic feet, such gas shall be assumed to have zero (0) pounds of water per one million (1,000,000) cubic feet (dry gas). 15. The terms “in writing” and “written”, as used herein, shall include facsimile and e-mail transmissions. 16. The term “Maximum Daily Quantity” or “MDQ”, as used herein, shall mean the maximum quantity of gas that Transporter shall have agreed to receive for transport on any Day under a Transportation Service Agreement, exclusive of quantities delivered by Shipper to reimburse Transporter for fuel and gas lost or unaccounted for. 17. The term "Mcf", as used herein, shall mean one thousand (1,000) cubic feet of gas. 18. The term "MMBtu", as used herein, shall mean one million (1,000,000) Btu. 19. The term “NGA”, as used herein, shall mean the Natural Gas Act of 1938. 20. The term “NGPA”, as used herein, shall mean the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978. 21. The term "point", as used herein without further qualification, shall also mean, where applicable, the plural thereof. 22. The term "quarter", as used herein, shall mean a period of three (3) consecutive calendar months beginning at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the first day of the first month and ending at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time on the first day of the month in which the next succeeding period of three (3) calendar months begins. 23. The terms "Shipper," "Transporter" and "party," as used herein, shall include any designee(s) of Shipper and Transporter. 24. The term "year", as used herein, shall mean a period of three hundred sixty-five (365) consecutive days beginning and ending at 9:00 a.m. Central Clock Time; provided, however, that any such period which contains the date of February 29 shall consist of three hundred sixty-six (366) consecutive days.
SECTION II. QUANTITIES AND SERVICE PROVIDED
1. Scope and Character of Service - Shipper shall have the right on any day to deliver to Transporter at the Receipt Point(s) quantities of gas up to and including Shipper's “MDQ”, as hereinafter defined. Transporter shall receive such gas and shall deliver an equivalent quantity at the Delivery Point(s) for Shipper's Account. Transporter's obligation to deliver gas at the Delivery Point(s) exists only so long and only in such quantity as Shipper continues to deliver gas into Transporter's facilities at the Receipt Point(s). Similarly, Transporter's obligation to accept receipt of Shipper's gas at the Receipt Point exists only so long and only in such quantity as Shipper continues to take delivery of gas made available at the Delivery Point(s). Shipper recognizes that the services hereunder are to be performed by Transporter on an interruptible basis and may be interrupted without notice, in whole or in part, from time to time in Transporter's sole discretion. The Parties agree that in no event shall an interruption of service constitute a breach of the Agreement and that Transporter shall not be liable to Shipper in damages or otherwise due to any interruption of service. 2. The Maximum Daily Quantity ("MDQ") - is set forth, as applicable, in the relevant confirmations executed pursuant to this Agreement or in such Agreement itself. In the event gas is received at any Receipt Point or redelivered at any Delivery Point in a commingled stream, Transporter shall have the sole right to allocate that portion of the commingled stream for Shipper's account attributable to the transportation service provided under the Agreement. 3. Allocation Statements - During the periods Transporter receives gas for Shipper and other parties at any third party-allocated Receipt Point provided under the terms of the Agreement at which no Operational Balancing Agreement is in effect, Shipper shall furnish or cause to be furnished to Transporter, a pre-determined allocation method prior to flow during the relevant month, setting forth (on a daily basis) the allocation of the total quantity of gas to be received by Transporter at each Receipt Point during such month. Shipper shall be bound by, and Transporter shall be entitled to rely conclusively on, such pre-determined allocation method. In regard to third party-measured Receipt Points, Shipper shall furnish a full tabulation of actual measured volumes by the fifth day of the month following the month of receipt. 4. Excess Receipt Quantities - In the event Shipper has quantities of gas available on any day for delivery to Transporter in excess of the MDQ, Shipper may tender such excess gas for delivery to Transporter, and Transporter may, in its sole discretion in each such instance, accept or refuse delivery of all or any part of such excess gas. Any excess gas so accepted by Transporter will be subject to all of the terms and provisions hereof. 5. Balancing - It is recognized that, because of dispatching and other operational variations, it may be physically impossible or operationally impractical for Transporter to redeliver to Shipper precisely Equivalent Quantities on any given day. Therefore, any difference between the Equivalent Quantity and the actual quantity of gas redelivered hereunder on any one day as calculated on an MMBtu basis ("imbalance") shall be computed and cashed out as hereinbelow provided. Any positive difference between the Equivalent Quantity on any day hereunder and actual redeliveries on such day shall be purchased by Transporter from Shipper at a price equal to the lesser of the Gas Daily Price for the day upon which such imbalance occurred and that for the second business day subsequent to the day of such occurrence. Any negative difference between the Equivalent Quantity on any day hereunder and actual redeliveries on such day shall be sold by Transporter to Shipper at a price equal to the higher of the Gas Daily Price for the day on which such imbalance occurred and that for the second business day subsequent to that of such occurrence. Transporter shall provide Shipper with a daily imbalance statement for each month, setting forth any daily imbalance and the basis thereof, expressed in MMBtu. Such statement shall also set forth the price relevant to the daily cashout of all such imbalances. 6. Nominations for Service - All nominations for transportation service shall be submitted by Shipper monthly through Transporter’s DART system or through written nomination forms, or through such other electronic or written means as Transporter shall specify, in accordance with Transporter's standard nomination cycles, as amended from time to time. Furthermore, Shipper shall be bound by and Transporter may rely conclusively on Shipper's nominated quantities as confirmed by Transporter. Any variance from the nominated quantities must be submitted in writing or through such electronic means as Shipper and Transporter shall agree. Transporter shall not be obligated to accept and/or confirm nominations for any day for receipt or delivery of gas at any point for which nominations in the aggregate are less than the minimum or greater than any maximum quantities set forth in the relevant Agreement between Transporter and Shipper. Transporter reserves the right to amend its nomination procedures from time to time.
SECTION III. MINIMUM QUANTITY
Transporter reserves the right to refuse to provide service or to terminate existing service at any Receipt Point whenever Shipper's delivery of gas at such Receipt Point is less than 1,000 MMBtu during any day. Transporter's right to terminate shall not apply if the deficiency is due to interruption of service by Transporter.
SECTION IV. DELIVERY PRESSURES
1. All gas delivered at the Receipt Point shall be delivered at pressures sufficient to enter Transporter's system at the working pressures maintained by Transporter at the Receipt Point from time to time. Transporter shall not be obligated to receive gas at pressures exceeding the Maximum Allowable Operating Pressures prescribed under any applicable governmental regulations. 2. All gas redelivered at the Delivery Point shall be redelivered at the working pressures maintained by Transporter at the Delivery Point from time to time. Shipper shall not be obligated to receive gas at pressures exceeding the Maximum Allowable Operating Pressures prescribed under any applicable governmental regulations.
SECTION V. METHOD OF MEASUREMENT AND MEASUREMENT EQUIPMENT
1. Assumed Atmospheric Pressure - The average atmospheric pressure shall be assumed to be fourteen and seven-tenths pounds per square inch absolute (14.7 psia). Where site conditions vary from this, at the option of Transporter, the actual atmospheric pressure shall be determined within one tenth pounds (0.1) and used based on actual elevation or location of the Receipt or Delivery Point(s). 2. Unit of Volume - The unit of volume for measurement of gas for all purposes shall be one (1) cubic foot of gas at a base temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60° F.) and at a pressure of fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch absolute (14.73 psia). Where measurement is by orifice meter, all fundamental constants, observations, records and procedures involved in the determination and/or verification of the quantity and other characteristics of gas delivered hereunder shall be in accordance with the standards prescribed in the latest edition of A.G.A. Report No. 3 (ANSI/API 2530) on "Orifice Metering of Natural Gas," with any revisions, amendments or supplements as may be mutually acceptable to Transporter and Shipper, unless otherwise specified herein. Measurement by turbine meter, unless specified otherwise, shall be in accordance with A.G.A. Report No. 7, with any revisions, amendments or supplements as may be mutually agreeable to the parties hereto. When positive displacement or turbine meters are used for the measurement of gas, the flowing temperature of the gas shall be assumed to be sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60° F.) and no correction shall be made for any variation therefrom; provided, however, both parties shall have the option of installing or causing to be installed a recording thermometer, and if either party exercises such option and installs or causes to be installed such thermometer, correction shall be made for each degree variation in the average flowing temperature for each meter recording. Where measurement is by ultrasonic meter, all fundamental constants, observations, records and procedures involved in the determination and/or verification of the quantity and other characteristics of gas delivered hereunder shall be in accordance with the standards prescribed in the latest edition of A.G .A. Report No. 9 on “Measurement of Gas by Multi Path Ultrasonic Meters” with any revisions, amendments or supplements as may be mutually acceptable to Transporter and Shipper, unless otherwise specified herein. Where measurement is by other than orifice, turbine or ultrasonic meter, standards commonly acceptable in the natural gas industry shall be used in the determination of all factors involved in the computation of gas volumes. 3. Basis - The measurement of gas hereunder shall be corrected for deviation from Boyle's Law at the pressures and temperatures under which gas is measured hereunder by use of the AGA Report No. 8 as referenced in the AGA Reports Nos. 3 and 9. 4. Determination of Heating Value - At the option of either party hereto, the heating value of the gas may be determined by the use of a chromatograph, a continuous gas sampler or by taking spot gas samples. The arithmetical average of the hourly heating value recorded by a recording instrument during periods of flow each day shall be considered as the heating value of the gas delivered to Transporter or Shipper as of the day the results are available. In the event a continuous gas sampler is installed, then the heating value of the composite sample shall be utilized in determination of heating value commencing with the first day of the month corresponding to the sample period. If spot samples are taken, the samples shall be run on the measuring party's chromatograph at another location. The result of a spot sample shall be applied to gas deliveries as of the day the results are available and for all succeeding days until a new sample is taken. All heating value determinations made with a chromatograph shall use physical gas constants for gas compounds as outlined in the GPA Std 2145-00 Rev 1 Table of Physical Constants of Paraffin Hydrocarbons and other Components of Natural Gas and any subsequent amendments or revisions to such report to which the parties may mutually agree. The moisture content of the gas shall be determined as often as necessary and practical to determine the actual heating value of the gas stream. Alternatively, regardless of the methodology used for heating value determination, Transporter may, in the exercise of reasonable judgment, choose to apply the results forward from the Day the data yielding the results is taken, after considering the operational characteristics and variability of gas composition. 5. Determination of Flowing Temperature - The temperature of the gas flowing through the meter or meters shall be determined by the continuous use of a recording thermometer installed so that it will properly record the temperature of the gas flowing through the meter or meters. 6. Determination of Specific Gravity - The specific gravity of the gas flowing through the meter or meters may be determined by the use of a chromatograph or by analysis of gas collected in spot and continuous samplers. Specific gravity shall be updated whenever the heating value of the gas is updated. All specific gravity determinations made with a chromatograph shall use physical gas constants for gas compounds as outlined in the GPA Std 2145-00 Rev 1 Table of Physical Constants of Paraffin Hydrocarbons and other Components of Natural Gas with any subsequent amendments or revisions to such report to which the parties may mutually agree. Specific gravity shall be determined to the nearest one thousandth (0.001). 7. Equipment - All facilities necessary to measure the gas at the points of Receipt and Delivery hereof shall have been installed and shall be in operation as of the in-service date of Transporter’s pipeline. Any necessary metering facilities which are installed subsequent to such date shall be installed, paid for, owned, operated and maintained as mutually agreeable between Shipper and Transporter. The operator of the measuring facilities at the respective points of receipt and delivery hereof shall operate and maintain, at its expense, said measuring equipment at the points of receipt and delivery hereunder. Each party shall have access to the measuring equipment operated by such operator at all reasonable times, but readings, calibrations and adjustments thereof shall be done by the employees or agents of the operator only.
Any new measurement and appurtenant facilities required at the Receipt Point and Delivery Point shall be installed, owned, operated and maintained by Transporter at Transporter's option. Shipper will reimburse Transporter for all costs incurred as a result of the installation of any such facilities including, without limitation, labor, materials and overhead. Additionally, Shipper shall pay to Transporter an amount, as reasonably calculated by Transporter, equal to Transporter's estimated federal and/or state income or other tax liability incurred as a result of and/or pursuant to the provisions of this Paragraph 7. Title to such facilities shall be and remain in Transporter.
If the measurement and appurtenant facilities are existing at the Receipt Point and Delivery Point, and such facilities are deemed adequate and operable in Transporter's sole determination, then such facilities shall be used; however, if any modification or expansion of any such existing facility is deemed necessary in Transporter's sole determination, Transporter shall notify Shipper. If Shipper notifies Transporter that Shipper desires to utilize that point in the future, then such modification or expansion shall be performed at Shipper's sole expense and Shipper agrees to reimburse Transporter for all costs incurred in such modification or expansion including, without limitation, labor, material and overhead. Title to such equipment shall be and remain in Transporter.
As specified by Transporter, all measuring stations which it owns or operates at the Receipt or Delivery Point(s) hereunder shall be equipped with orifice meter runs, orifice meter gauges, recording gauges or other types of meter or meters of standard make and design commonly accepted in the natural gas industry in order to accurately measure the gas delivered to Transporter or Shipper hereunder. At Transporter's election, a computer, transducers and other associated sensing devices may be installed to accurately measure the gas at the metering points which it owns or operates hereunder in accordance with AGA Report Nos. 3, 5, 6, 7, 8 and 9 as appropriate, in lieu of mechanical devices. If a computer and associated devices are installed, gas quality values will be entered either manually or as real time data if such data is available. All gas quality values used in super compressibility correction determinations shall be entered as real time data if such data is available or, if the gas quality source is a composite or spot sample, the values shall be entered manually each time they are determined at intervals mutually agreed upon, but at least once every six (6) months. Any additional facilities for the delivery of gas to Transporter or Shipper hereunder which are requested by Shipper shall be installed by Transporter and Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for the cost of such installation and for the facilities so installed. Such cost shall include, without limitation, labor, materials and overhead. Title to such facilities shall be and remain in Transporter.
Any reimbursement due Transporter pursuant to this Paragraph 7 shall be made within fifteen (15) days of Shipper's receipt of Transporter's detailed invoice for same. 8. Calibration and Tests of Meters - If used, chromatographs shall be calibrated by the measuring party against a standard gas sample at least once per month. All other measuring equipment shall be calibrated and adjusted as necessary by the measuring party but at least once each quarter if gas is flowing at a minimum daily average flow rate of at least 500 Mcf for the quarter, or as frequently as deemed necessary by the operator of such measuring equipment but not more than once each month. The other party may, at its option, be present for such calibration and adjustment. The measuring party shall give the other party notice of the time of all tests sufficiently in advance of conducting same so that both parties may conveniently have their representatives present. Following any test, any measuring equipment found to be inaccurate to any degree shall be adjusted immediately to measure accurately. Each party shall have the right, at any time, to challenge the accuracy of any measuring equipment used hereunder and may request additional tests. If, upon testing, the challenged equipment is found to be in error, then it shall be repaired and calibrated. The cost of any such special testing, repair and calibration shall be borne by the party requiring the special test if the percentage of inaccuracy is found to be one percent (1%) or less; otherwise, the cost shall be borne by the party operating the challenged measuring equipment. 9. Access to Meters and Records - The other party shall have access at all reasonable times to the measuring equipment and all other instruments used by the measuring party in determining the measurement and quality of the gas delivered to Transporter or Shipper hereunder, but the reading, calibrating, and adjusting thereof shall be done only by employees, agents or representatives of the measuring party. The records shall be kept on file by the measuring party for a period of one (1) year for mutual use of Transporter and Shipper. Upon request, the measuring party shall submit to the other party records from such equipment, subject to return by that party within thirty (30) days after receipt thereof. 10. Correction of Metering Errors - If, upon any test, the measuring equipment in the aggregate is found to be inaccurate by more than one percent (1%), registration thereof and any payments based upon such registration shall be corrected at the rate of such inaccuracy for any period of inaccuracy which is definitely known or agreed upon; provided, however, if such period is not definitely known or agreed upon, then such registration and payment shall be corrected for a period extending back one-half (l/2) of the time elapsed since the date of the prior calibration. (but with such corrected period not to exceed ninety (90) days). 11. Failure of Meters - If, for any reason, the measuring equipment is out of service or out of repair so that the quantity of gas delivered through such measuring equipment cannot be ascertained or computed from the readings thereof, the quantity of gas so delivered during the period such equipment is out of service or out of repair shall be estimated and agreed upon by Transporter and Shipper upon the basis of the best available data, using the first of the following methods which is feasible: (a) By using the registration of any duplicate measuring equipment installed by the measuring party, if installed and registering correctly; (b) By correcting the error if the percentage of error is ascertainable by calibration, test or mathematical calculation; (c) By using the registration of any check measuring equipment of the other party, if installed and registering accurately; or (d) By estimating the quantity of deliveries by using the volumes delivered to Transporter or Shipper, as applicable, under similar conditions during preceding periods when the measuring equipment was registering accurately. 12. Check Measuring Equipment - Each party may install, maintain and operate at its own expense such check measuring equipment as desired; provided, however, that such equipment shall be installed so as not to interfere with the operation of any other measuring equipment. Each party shall have access to the check meter(s) so installed by the other party at all reasonable times, but the reading, calibration and adjusting thereof shall be done only by the employees, agents or representatives of the operator thereof. 13. New Measurement Techniques - If, at any time during the term hereof, a new method or technique is developed with respect to gas measurement or to the determination of the factors used in such gas measurement, such new method or technique may be substituted for the method set forth in this Section V. when, in the opinion of the parties, employing such new method or technique is advisable. SECTION VI. QUALITY
1. Specifications at Receipt and Delivery Points - All gas received by Transporter from Shipper and delivered by Transporter to Shipper under the terms of the Agreement shall conform to the following specifications: (a) The gas shall be free of water, hydrocarbons in liquid form and other objectionable liquids at the temperature and pressure at which the gas is delivered to Transporter and the gas shall not contain any hydrocarbons which might condense to free liquids under normal conditions and shall in no event contain water vapor in excess of seven (7) pounds per one million (1,000,000) cubic feet, measured at fourteen and seventy-three hundredths pounds per square inch absolute (14.73 psia) at a standard temperature of sixty degrees Fahrenheit (60° F.). (b) The gas shall not contain more than twenty-five hundredths (0.25) of one grain of hydrogen sulfide per one hundred (100) cubic feet as determined by quantitative methods in general use within the natural gas industry and as mutually acceptable to the parties hereto. (c) The gas shall not contain more than one half (0.50) of one grain of total sulfur per one hundred (100) cubic feet as determined by quantitative methods in general use within the natural gas industry and as mutually acceptable to the parties hereto. (d) The gas shall not contain more than twenty-five hundredths (0.25) of one grain of mercaptans per one hundred (100) cubic feet as determined by quantitative methods in general use within the natural gas industry and as mutually acceptable to the parties hereto. (e) The gas shall not contain in excess of two percent (2%) by volume of carbon dioxide. (f) The gas shall not contain in excess of ten parts per million (10 ppm) by volume of uncombined oxygen, and the parties shall make reasonable efforts to maintain the gas free from oxygen. (g) The gas shall not contain in excess of three percent (3%) by volume of nitrogen. (h) The gas shall not contain in excess of two-tenths (0.2) gallon per Mcf of isopentane and heavier hydrocarbons. (i) In the aggregate, the gas shall not contain in excess of three percent (3%) by volume of non-hydrocarbons. (j) The gas shall contain no carbon monoxide, halogens or unsaturated hydrocarbons and not more than four hundred parts per million (400 ppm) of hydrogen. (k) The gas shall have a temperature of not more than one hundred and twenty degrees (120°) Fahrenheit and not less than forty degrees (40°)Fahrenheit. (l) The gas shall contain a daily average heating content of not less than nine hundred fifty (950) Btu per cubic foot. Such daily average heating content shall not be in excess of one thousand, one hundred (1,100) Btu per cubic foot. (m) The gas shall be commercially free of dust, gum, gum-forming constituents, or other objectionable liquid or solid matter which might become separated from the gas in the course of transmission through pipelines. (n) The gas shall be free of any and all corrosive materials that may, in Transporter's determination, be harmful to its facilities. (o) The gas shall have a hydrocarbon dewpoint below 40 degrees (40°) Fahrenheit. 2. Failure to Meet Quality Specifications - In the event either party determines the gas delivered to it fails to meet the quality specifications prescribed above, such party shall have the right without notice to immediately terminate the receipt of any gas so delivered failing to meet such quality specifications, but shall as soon as practical notify in writing the other party of such action and the basis thereof. Notwithstanding the foregoing, at its sole discretion, Transporter may continue to accept gas that does not meet the foregoing quality specifications. In such an event Transporter may charge to Shipper a conditioning fee relevant to such gas that fails to meet quality specifications. The amount of such conditioning fee shall be determined by Transporter utilizing a commercially reasonable methodology. Transporter shall notify Shipper within thirty (30) days of its assessment of such a conditioning fee hereunder.
SECTION VII. FORCE MAJEURE
1. In the event of either party being rendered unable wholly or in part by force majeure to carry out its obligations under the Agreement, other than to make payments thereunder, it is agreed that on such party giving notice and full particulars of such force majeure in writing to the other party as soon as possible after the occurrence of the cause relied on, then the obligations of the party giving such notice, so far as they are affected by such force majeure, shall be suspended during the continuance of any inability so caused but for no longer period, and such cause shall as far as possible be remedied with all reasonable dispatch. 2. a) The term "force majeure" as employed herein shall include acts of God, strikes, lockouts or other industrial disturbances, acts of public enemy, sabotage, wars, blockades, insurrections, riots, epidemics, landslides, lightning, earthquakes, fires, storms, floods, high water, washouts, hurricanes or other natural disasters, threat of physical harm or damage resulting in the evacuation or shut down of facilities necessary for the production or delivery or receipt or use of gas, arrests and restraints of governments and people, governmental statutes, rules, orders or regulations of whatever kind or type, civil disturbances, explosions, breakage or accident to machinery or lines of pipe or facilities in which the gas is used, the necessity for testing or for making repairs or alterations to wells, machinery, facilities or lines of pipe through which the gas is moved, or freezing of wells or lines of pipe or facilities through which the gas is moved or in which the gas is used, partial or entire failure of wells, processing, gathering or transportation facilities or gasification and gas manufacturing facilities or facilities in which the gas is used, the orders of any court or governmental authority or agency having or asserting jurisdiction or the refusal or withdrawal of any necessary order, certificate or permit by any court or governmental authority or agency having or asserting jurisdiction, any acts of omissions (including, without limitation, failure to take, transport or deliver gas) of a transporter of gas to or for Transporter or Shipper, and any other causes, whether of the kind herein enumerated or otherwise, not reasonably within the control of the party claiming suspension and which by the exercise of due diligence such party is unable to prevent or overcome; such term shall likewise include, (a) in those instances where either party is required to obtain servitudes, rights-of-way grants, permits, certificates or licenses to enable such party to fulfill its obligations under the Agreement, the inability of such party to acquire or the delays on the part of such party in acquiring, at reasonable cost and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such servitudes, rights-of-way grants, permits or certificates or licenses, and (b) in those instances where either party is required to furnish materials and supplies for the purpose of constructing or maintaining facilities or is required to secure permits or permissions from any governmental agency to enable such party to fulfill its obligations under the Agreement, the inability of such party to acquire or the delays on the part of such party in acquiring, at reasonable cost and after the exercise of reasonable diligence, such materials and supplies, permits or permissions. b) It is understood and agreed that the settlement of strikes or lockouts shall be entirely within the discretion of the party having the difficulty and that the above requirement that any force majeure shall be remedied with all reasonable dispatch shall not require the settlement of strikes or lockouts by acceding to the demands of the opposing person when such course is inadvisable in the discretion of the party having the difficulty. c) Either party may partially or entirely interrupt its performance under the Agreement for the purpose of making necessary or desirable inspections, alterations and repairs, but only for such time as may be reasonable; and that party requiring such relief shall give to the other party reasonable notice of its intention to suspend its performance thereunder, except in cases of emergency where such notice is impracticable and shall endeavor to arrange such interruption so as to inconvenience the other party as little as reasonably possible. 3. Notwithstanding the foregoing, it is specifically understood and agreed by the parties that force majeure shall in no way terminate the parties' obligations to balance volumes of gas hereunder.
SECTION VIII. TAXES AND FEE REIMBURSEMENT
In addition to paying the fee provided in the Agreement, Shipper shall also reimburse Transporter for taxes and certain other fees as follows:
1. Tax Reimbursement - Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for all taxes which are levied upon and/or paid by Transporter with respect to the transportation services performed hereunder and under the terms of the Agreement. Without in any manner limiting the foregoing, it is specifically agreed that Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for any state utilities taxes to which Transporter may be subject due to its receipt and/or delivery of gas hereunder. 2. Reimbursement of Fees Subsequent to the in-service date of Transporter’s pipeline, Shipper shall reimburse Transporter for any and all filing fees in connection with providing transportation services to Shipper hereunder that Transporter is required to pay by any governmental authority having or asserting jurisdiction.
SECTION IX. BILLING, ACCOUNTING AND REPORTING
1. Accounting Statements - Transporter shall render to Shipper, on or before the tenth (l0th) day of each calendar month (i) a statement setting forth, with respect to all gas received by Transporter during the preceding month at the Receipt Point, the total quantity and the heating value of said gas, (ii) a statement setting forth, with respect to all gas redelivered to Shipper during the preceding month at the Delivery Point, the total quantity and the heating value of said gas, (iii) the transportation charge therefore and any other charges due Transporter under the Agreement or these General Terms and Conditions and (iv) a statement setting forth all daily imbalances and detailing the cashout thereof. Transporter may initially bill on its best reasonably available estimates if all actual information is not available at the time the statement is to be sent. Shipper agrees to make payment to Transporter within a ten (10) day period following receipt of Transporter's statement for all gas received by Transporter from Shipper at the Receipt Point during the preceding billing month and any other charges due Transporter under the Agreement or these General Terms and Conditions. 2. Late Payment - In the event Shipper fails to pay any amount due Transporter when the same is due, the unpaid balance shall bear interest from the due date until the date when same is paid at a variable rate ("Variable Rate") equal to the "prime rate" of interest published by Citibank, N.A. plus one percent (1%), each change in the Variable Rate to be effective without notice on the effective date of each change in the prime rate; provided, however, that the Variable Rate chargeable hereunder shall never exceed the maximum non-usurious rate of interest allowed by applicable law. In the event such failure to pay continues for a period of thirty (30) days, Transporter may, in addition to its other remedies, terminate this Agreement. 3. Errors and Disputes in Statements - In the event an error is discovered in the amount billed in any statement rendered by Transporter, such error shall be adjusted within thirty (30) days of the discovery of the error. In the event a dispute arises as to the amount payable in any statement rendered, Shipper shall nevertheless pay the total amount payable to Transporter under the statement rendered pending resolution of the dispute. Such payment shall not be deemed to be a waiver of the right by Shipper to recoup any overpayment, which shall be repaid by Transporter together with interest calculated under the method set forth in Paragraph 2. of this Section IX. 4. Examination of Books and Records - Each party shall have the right at reasonable hours to examine the books and records of the other party to the extent necessary to verify the accuracy of any statement, calculation or determination made pursuant to the provisions contained herein. If any such examination shall reveal, or if either party shall discover, any error in its own or the other party's statements, calculations or determinations, then proper adjustment and correction thereof shall be made as promptly as practicable thereafter. 5. Finality - Any statement or payment shall be final unless questioned within one (1) year of its date.
SECTION X. CREDITWORTHINESS OF SHIPPER
1. Evaluation of Credit - In evaluating requests for service and for certain other purposes under this Tariff, Transporter will perform a credit appraisal of Shipper.
(a) Acceptance of Shipper's request for service and the continuation of service are contingent upon Shipper satisfying creditworthiness requirements on an on-going basis. To determine creditworthiness, a credit appraisal shall be performed in accordance with the following criteria:
(i) Transporter shall apply consistent evaluation practices to all similarly situated Shippers to determine Shipper's financial ability to perform the payment obligations due to Transporter over the term of the requested or existing Agreement.
(ii) Shipper will be deemed creditworthy if:
(1) its long-term unsecured debt securities are rated at least BBB- by Standard & Poor's Corporation ("S&P") and at least Baa3 by Moody's Investor Service ("Moody's") (provided, however, that if Shipper's rating is at BBB- or Baa3 and the short-term or long-term outlook is Negative, Transporter may require further analysis as discussed below); and (2) the sum of commodity fees and any other associated fees and charges for the contract term is less than 15% of Shipper's tangible net worth. For the purposes of this Section X, the term "tangible net worth" shall mean for a corporation the sum of the capital stock, paid-in capital in excess of par or stated value, and other free and clear equity reserve accounts less goodwill, patents, unamortized loan costs or restructuring costs, and other intangible assets. Only actual tangible assets are included in Transporter's assessment of creditworthiness. If Shipper has multiple Agreements with Transporter, then the total potential fees and charges of all such Agreements shall be considered in determining creditworthiness.
(iii) If Shipper does not meet the criteria described above, then Shipper may request that Transporter evaluate its creditworthiness based upon the level of service requested relative to Shipper's current and future ability to meet its obligations. Such credit appraisal shall be based upon Transporter's evaluation of the following information and credit criteria:
(1) S&P and Moody's opinions, watch alerts, and rating actions and reports, rating, opinions and other actions by Dun and Bradstreet and other credit reporting agencies will be considered in determining creditworthiness. (2) Consistent financial statement analysis will be applied by Transporter to determine the acceptability of Shipper's current and future financial strength. Shipper's balance sheets, income statements, cash flow statements and auditor's notes will be analyzed along with key ratios and trends regarding liquidity, asset management, debt management, debt coverage, capital structure, operational efficiency and profitability. (3) Results of bank and trade reference checks and credit reports must demonstrate that Shipper is paying its obligations in a timely manner. (4) Shipper must not be operating under any chapter of the bankruptcy laws and must not be subject to liquidation or debt reduction procedures under state laws and there must not be pending any petition for involuntary bankruptcy. An exception may be made if Shipper is a debtor in possession operating under Chapter XI of the Federal Bankruptcy Act and Transporter is assured that the service billing will be paid promptly as a cost of administration under the federal court's jurisdiction, based on a court order in effect, and if Shipper is continuing and continues in the future actually to make payment. (5) Whether Shipper is subject to any lawsuits or judgments outstanding which could materially impact its ability to remain solvent. (6) Whether Shipper has or has had any delinquent balances outstanding for services provided previously by Transporter and whether Shipper is paying and has paid its account balances according to the terms established in its Agreements (excluding amounts as to which there is a good faith dispute). (7) The nature of Shipper's business and the effect on that business of general economic conditions and economic conditions specific to it, including Shipper's ability to recover the costs of Transporter's services through filings with regulatory agencies or otherwise to pass on such costs to its customers. (8) Any other information, including any information provided by Shipper, that is relevant to Shipper's current and future financial strength and Shipper's ability to make full payment over the term of the contract.
(iv) Information which Transporter may request to be provided by Shipper to Transporter in connection with such a credit evaluation includes the following:
(1) Audited Financial Statements; (2) Annual Report; (3) Most recent filed statements with the Securities and Exchange Commission (or an equivalent authority) or other similar publicly available information; (4) For public entities, the most recent publicly available interim financial statements, with an attestation by its Chief Financial Officer, Controller, or equivalent (CFO) that such statements constitute a true, correct, and fair representation of Shipper's financial condition prepared in accordance with Generally Accepted Accounting Principles (GAAP) or equivalent; (5) For non-public entities, including those that are state-regulated utilities, the most recent available interim financial statements, with an attestation by its CFO that such statements constitute a true, correct, and fair representation of Shipper's financial condition prepared in accordance with GAAP or equivalent; (6) For non-public entities, including those that are state-regulated utilities, an existing sworn filing, including the most recent available interim financial statements and annual financial reports filed with the respective regulatory authority, showing Shipper's current financial condition; (7) For state-regulated utility local distribution companies, documentation from their respective state regulatory commission (or an equivalent authority) of an authorized gas supply cost recovery mechanism; (8) List of affiliates, parent companies, and subsidiaries; (9) Publicly available credit reports from credit and bond rating agencies; (10) Private credit ratings, if obtained by Shipper; (11) Bank references; (12) Trade references; (13) Statement of legal composition; and (14) Statement of the length of time the business has been in operation.
(v) If Transporter concludes that Shipper is not creditworthy, Transporter shall provide written notice to Shipper within ten (10) days after that determination is made. If requested by Shipper, Transporter shall provide a written explanation of the reasons for this determination. Shipper may challenge Transporter's determination by providing a written rebuttal to Transporter's explanation within ten (10) days after the explanation is provided by Transporter. Transporter shall respond to such a rebuttal in writing within ten (10) days. Any reevaluation of credit by Transporter in response to such a rebuttal by Shipper shall be based on the credit criteria set out in this Section X.
b) If Shipper fails to satisfy the credit criteria, Shipper may still obtain or continue service hereunder if Shipper, at its sole discretion, provides the security required under one of the following options:
(i) payment in advance of all fees and charges for three (3) months' service; (ii) a standby irrevocable letter of credit covering all fees and charges for three (3) months' service drawn upon a bank acceptable to Transporter; (iii) security interest covering all fees and charges for three (3) months' service in collateral provided by Shipper found to be satisfactory to Transporter; or (iv) guarantee of all fees and charges for three (3) months' service by a person or another entity which does satisfy the credit appraisal.
(c) Where Shipper selects the prepayment option under Paragraph 1(b)(i) of this Section X, the prepayment amounts shall be deposited in an interest-bearing escrow account if such an account has been established by Shipper which meets the criteria set out in this paragraph. The costs of establishing and maintaining the escrow account shall be borne by Shipper. The escrow bank must be rated at least AA or better and shall not be affiliated with Shipper. The escrow arrangement shall provide for the prepayment amounts to be applied against Shipper's obligation under its Agreement(s) with Transporter and shall grant Transporter a security interest in such amounts as an assurance of future performance. The escrow arrangement shall specify the permitted investments of escrowed funds so as to protect principal, and shall include only such investment options as corporations typically use for short-term deposit of their funds. Such escrow account shall at all times maintain the amount of prepayment required under Paragraph 1(b)(i) of this Section X. If Transporter is required to draw down the funds in escrow, it will notify Shipper and Shipper must replenish such funds within three (3) Business Days after such notice.
(d) Transporter's credit appraisal procedures involve the establishment of dollar credit limits on a standardized, nondiscriminatory basis. To the extent that Shipper's accounts with Transporter do not exceed such limit, and Shipper has met all creditworthiness requirements as determined in periodic credit reviews by Transporter, which reviews may be conducted on at least an annual basis, no new credit appraisals shall be required when an existing Agreement is amended or a request for a new Agreement is made, provided that Shipper's payment history has been satisfactory and there is no bona fide basis for questioning Shipper's creditworthiness, subject to the provisions of Paragraph 3 of this Section X
(e) In the event Transporter constructs new lateral facilities to accommodate a Shipper, Transporter may require from the Shipper security in an amount up to the cost of the facilities. This provision does not apply to mainline expansions. Such security may be in any of the forms available under Paragraph 1(b) of this Section X, at Shipper's choice. Transporter is only permitted to recover the cost of facilities once, either through rates or through this provision. As Transporter recovers the cost of these facilities through its rates, the security required shall be reduced accordingly. Specifically, collateral provided by a Shipper related to new facilities shall be returned to that Shipper in equal monthly amounts over the term of its contract for service related to the new facilities or as otherwise mutually agreed by Transporter and Shipper. Where facilities are constructed to serve multiple Shippers, an individual Shipper's obligation hereunder shall be for no more than its proportionate share of the cost of the facilities. This requirement is in addition to and shall not supersede or replace any other rights that Transporter may have regarding the construction and reimbursement of facilities.
(f) Transporter may not take any action under this Section X which conflicts with any order of the U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
2. Delinquency in Payment – (a) Irrespective of any otherwise applicable priority, Transporter may suspend service to any Shipper which is delinquent in payments under any Agreement, subject to the following conditions:
(i) Transporter shall give Shipper written notice of the delinquency and of Transporter's intent to suspend service if the deficiency is not cured. If the delinquency is not remedied within fifteen (15) days of such notice, Transporter may suspend service. Transporter shall simultaneously provide written notice to FERC of any such suspension. (ii) If Shipper is again deficient in payment within six (6) months after the prior deficiency, then Transporter may suspend service to Shipper within five (5) Business Days after providing notice hereunder unless Shipper remedies the deficiency within that time period.
(b) In addition to suspension, Transporter may terminate service if Shipper fails to remedy a delinquency in payment. Any such termination requires thirty (30) days' prior notice to Shipper and to FERC. To avoid termination, Shipper must remedy the deficiency within this notice period. Such notice may be given simultaneously with the initial notice under Paragraph 2(a)(i) of this Section X or with the notice under Paragraph 2(a)(ii) of this Section X.
(c) In the event of a good faith billing dispute, withholding of payment for the amount in dispute by Shipper shall not be considered a delinquency in payment, consistent with Section IX of these General Terms and Conditions, and will not result in suspension or termination of service.
(d) Transporter may not take any action under this Section X which conflicts with any order of the U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
3. Deterioration of Credit – (a) (i) If at any time Transporter reasonably determines, based on adequate information available to it, that Shipper is not creditworthy under Paragraph 1(a) of this Section X or if Shipper fails to maintain assurance of future performance under Paragraph 1(b) of this Section X, Transporter may notify Shipper in writing that it has five (5) Business Days to provide Transporter with security consistent with Paragraph 1(b) of this Section X which is adequate to cover all charges for one month's advance service. In addition, within thirty (30) days after such notification, Shipper must fully comply with the means for adequate assurance of future performance, covering three (3) full months of advance service from the end of such 30-day notice period, as provided under Paragraph 1(b) of this Section X. If Shipper has not satisfied the requirements in either of the prior two (2) sentences by the end of the specified prior notice period, Transporter may immediately suspend service to Shipper. Transporter may terminate service if it has complied with the procedures in Paragraph 3(d) of this Section X. (ii) If Transporter does not have sufficient information to determine whether Shipper is creditworthy, it may request additional information in writing from Shipper consistent with Paragraph 1(a) of this Section X, and Shipper must provide such information within five (5) Business Days. If Shipper fails to provide the requested information or if Transporter determines that Shipper is not creditworthy based on such information, Paragraph 2(a)(i) of this Section X shall apply for suspension of service and Paragraph 3(d) of this Section X shall apply for termination of service.
b) Any suspension of service hereunder shall continue until Transporter is reasonably satisfied that Shipper is creditworthy under Paragraph 1(a) of this Section X or until Shipper has provided adequate assurance of future performance under Paragraph 1(b) of this Section X.
c) If Transporter has determined Shipper to be not creditworthy, Shipper may at any time request that its credit status be reevaluated by providing Transporter with additional or updated information. Such reevaluation shall be performed consistent with Paragraph 1(a) of this Section X. After Transporter's receipt of such a request for credit reevaluation including all required information under this Tariff for evaluation of credit, Transporter shall provide a written response to Shipper within five (5) Business Days. Such written response should include either a determination of creditworthiness status, clearly stating the reason(s) for Transporter's decision, or an explanation supporting a future date by which a reevaluation determination will be made. In no event should such reevaluation determination exceed twenty (20) Business Days from the date of the receipt of Shipper's Request unless the parties mutually agree to some later date. If Transporter determines that Shipper is now creditworthy, any security requirement under Paragraph 1(b) of this Section X shall be terminated and any prepayment amounts (including any applicable interest) released to Shipper from escrow within five (5) Business Days after such determination.
d) In addition to suspension, Transporter may terminate service if Shipper fails to provide adequate assurance of future performance consistent with Paragraph 1(b) of this Section X. Any such termination requires thirty (30) days' prior notice to Shipper and to FERC. To avoid termination, Shipper must satisfy Paragraph 1(b) of this Section X within this notice period. Such notice may be given simultaneously with the notice provided for in Paragraph 3(a)(i) of this Section X.
e) In addition to any prior notice provided for above, Transporter shall simultaneously notify FERC in writing of any suspension or termination of service under this Paragraph 3.
f) Transporter may not take any action under this Paragraph 3 which conflicts with any order of the U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
SECTION XI. GOVERNMENTAL REGULATIONS
1. General - The Agreement and all operations hereunder are subject to all present and future applicable federal and state laws and the applicable ordinances, orders, rules and regulations of any local, state or federal governmental authority having or asserting jurisdiction; but nothing contained herein shall be construed as a waiver of any right to question or contest any such law, ordinance, order, rule or regulation in any forum having jurisdiction in the premises.
2. Filings - Transporter shall file all necessary applications, reports and/or notices required by Subpart G of Part 284 of FERC’s regulations, and Shipper shall provide Transporter with any necessary compliance information requested by Transporter in connection with preparing such reports.
3. Right of Termination - Transporter may cancel the Agreement on ten (10) days' written notice to Shipper if at any time any governmental or regulatory authority or official having or asserting jurisdiction takes any action (including, without limitation, issuance of a "policy statement") whereby the receipt, transportation and/or delivery of gas as contemplated hereunder or pursuant to other agreements subject to Subpart G of Part 284 of FERC’s regulations shall be prohibited or subjected to terms, conditions, restraints or regulations, (including, but not limited to, rate or price controls, or ceilings or open access requirements) which, in the judgment of Transporter, are unduly or overly burdensome; provided, however, that nothing contained herein shall preclude the Transporter and Shipper from renegotiating the Agreement if they so choose.
4. Shipper's Warranty - Execution of the Agreement by Shipper shall serve as a warranty to Transporter that all gas delivered to Transporter for transportation hereunder and under the terms of the Agreement shall be eligible for transportation in interstate commerce under applicable rules, regulations or orders of FERC without subjecting the facilities of Transporter to regulation under the NGA. Shipper will indemnify Transporter and save it harmless from all suits, actions, damages, costs, losses, expenses (including reasonable attorney fees) and regulatory proceedings arising from breach of this warranty.
SECTION XII. CAPACITY ALLOCATION
1. Priorities of Interruption – If, for whatever reason, Transporter is unable to (i) transport all quantities of gas nominated by Shippers under its gas transportation agreements, and (ii) to provide all gas nominated by its sales customers pursuant to their agreements with Transporter, Transporter shall interrupt service under such transportation and sales agreements, in whole or in part, on all or such portions of Transporter's system as may be necessary in Transporter's sole discretion; provided, however, that Transporter will act as a reasonably prudent pipeline operator, subject to operating necessities, to interrupt service (on that portion or portions of its system where such interruption is required) in accordance with the following schedule of priorities, beginning with the first service to be interrupted and continuing in order as necessary to the last service to be interrupted:
a.) Interruptible transportation service rendered pursuant to Transporter’s Blanket Certificate. b.) Interruptible intrastate transportation service. c.) Interruptible sales by Transporter. d.) Firm intrastate transportation service. e.) Firm sales by Transporter.
Within priority a.) above, interruption shall be administered so that service under the lowest priced contract is interrupted first and service under the highest priced contract is interrupted last.
2. Shipper's Right to Terminate - In the event an interruption requiring allocation of capacity pursuant to this Section XII persists for a continuous period of ten (10) days, Shipper shall have the right, on ten (10) days' written notice to Transporter, to terminate the Agreement. Such election to terminate shall be Shipper's sole and exclusive remedy for any interruption of service hereunder. 3. Modification of or Additions to Facilities - Transporter shall not be required to modify existing facilities or add new facilities in order to increase its capacity for service under the Agreement.
SECTION XIII. POSSESSION OF GAS
As between Shipper and Transporter, Transporter shall be deemed to be in exclusive control and possession of the gas and responsible for any damages, injuries or deaths caused thereby after receipt of such gas at the Receipt Point until the same shall have been redelivered to Shipper at the Delivery Point. Furthermore, as between Shipper and Transporter, Shipper shall be deemed to be in exclusive control and possession of the gas and responsible for any damages, injuries or deaths caused thereby prior to delivery of such gas to Transporter at the Receipt Point and after such gas shall have been redelivered for Shipper's account at the Delivery Point.
